John Edward: Knowledge of languages is of great importance to the citizens of the world
Independent schools in Scotland continue the tradition of brilliant education, which was once again confirmed in 2018: the outstanding results of the exams demonstrated individual and collective successes in sports, arts, music and other socially significant disciplines.
These schools are part of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), where more than 30,000 students are trained throughout Scotland, and aim to provide the highest level of services for students and their parents.
Independent schools seek to prepare their students for further higher education, the careers they choose, as well as for the status of citizens of the world.
As part of the education sector, which is responsible for the development and implementation of an individual school program, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a person in a language he understands, you are calling to his mind.
If you speak to him in his native language, you turn to his heart.”
It is a convincing proof that we cannot rely only on the English language if we want to build relationships with the citizens of other countries and be able to trust them.
Based on the results of this year’s latest exams, we see that languages occupy the leading positions in league tables and have the highest score on exam results in independent schools.
In total, 68 per cent of the students who studied foreign languages received a higher A rating.
Data from 74 SCIS schools showed that 72 per cent of students received an “A” in Mandarin, while 72 per cent of German learners, 69 per cent of French learners and 63 per cent of Spanish learners also received an “A”.
This proves that in independent schools in Scotland, foreign languages are undoubtedly considered vital for children and young people in the future.
Currently, language subjects are in the same demand as natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and other educational institutions.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 showed that among the reasons that made employers difficult to fill vacancies, 17 per cent were due to a lack of language skills.
Thus, language skills are increasingly becoming the key to a successful future career for young people.
Given that more promising jobs require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what profession the student will choose if he learns a second language, in the future he will gain a real advantage by mastering another additional skill that will benefit him throughout his further life.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a person who knows several foreign languages a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were not able to speak a foreign language well enough to support a conversation, while French was the only language with a two-digit percentage – 15 percent of English speakers speak it.
That’s why investing in language education is so important now.
Knowledge of several languages, especially the languages of developing economies, will give children more chances of finding a good job.
In schools in Scotland, there is a fairly large spread in terms of the languages taught — each school has its own set of languages.
A number of schools focus on more classic modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK in light of the future development of the country by 2020 – such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interests, in independent schools there will always be a choice of several languages with a teaching staff whose members are specialists in these languages.
Scottish independent schools seek to create a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills needed to succeed, no matter what the future awaits them.
At present, it cannot be denied that in the global business environment, languages are still vital for the future development of the country, so that should be reflected in education accordingly.
In fact, modern languages really need to be seen as “skills of international communication.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, providing diversity and benefits for the young people of Scotland.
We have to do it right.
John Edwards, Director of the Board of Independent Schools of Scotland
