Harvard students learn to rest in special courses
The new course, introduced this year at Harvard University, helped all elementary school students learn more to sleep and fight against the chauvinist culture of uninterrupted caffeine consumption in order to wake up to the “nights of spring.”
One of the academics found that the most successful students in the world often have no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chassler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
After his discovery, he was inspired by the idea of introducing such a course, in advance of a report on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning processes.
“At the end of my report, a girl approached me and said, ‘It’s a pity that I learned about it only now that I’m almost finished.’
She said no one ever told her about the importance of sleep — which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, first offered to students this year, talks about how a healthy sleep habit contributes to academic and sports performance, as well as how it improves a person’s overall well-being.
Paul Barrera, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s Health Service, says the university decided to introduce this course after it was discovered that students experienced a serious lack of sleep during the course.
The class lasts one hour, students perform a number of interactive tasks.
In one section of the class, an image of the room in the dormitory is offered, where students, by clicking on coffee cups, curtains, exercisers and books, get information about how each of these actions and substances — the daily amount of coffee, the light, which cause sleep deficiency — affect the outcome.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression and cancer.
The interactive campus map encourages the participants to think about their daily lives.
“We understand that these classes will not change the behavior of students at once.
But we believe that they have the right to know, like any other person has the right to know about, for example, how smoking affects his health,” added Professor Chasler.
According to him, the false sense of pride that a person can “sleep all night” is still widespread, and modern technologies, as well as increasing pressure on students, mean that sleep deprivation is becoming a problem.
According to him, a sufficient amount of good quality sleep is a student’s “secret weapon” to fight stress, nervous exhaustion and anxiety, and even to fight overweight, as insomnia turns the brain into hunger.
Raymond Soe, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Chasler develop a course by attending one of the classes last year during his first year of study at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to spread this information across the campus.
He hopes that the next step is to ask all graduates to go through a similar curriculum before entering a competitive educational institution.
Professor Chasler advises students to set up a alarm clock warning that they need to lie down and wake up, as well as remember the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lamps, which disrupts the human biorhythm and leads to problems.
