The study, organised by the Scottish National Foundation, will study the common illusory, illusory soprano, as well as the brown long-haired flying mice and Dobanton nocturnals inhabiting Inverewe Gardens, Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be installed at some points around the site to track the actions of flying mice throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile field surveys using handheld detectors.
An expert sound analysis of all records will determine the frequency of screams, as well as the activities for which different groups of these animals are responsible.
Then a map of the habitat will be drawn up and a report prepared to create a detailed picture of their behavior on a landscape scale.
Rob Duar, NTS Nature Conservation Advisor, hopes that these results will show which habitats are most important for flying mice and how they are used by each species.
This information will help identify the main areas of work on the management of the habitat, such as the formation of ponds, as well as ways to maintain forest massifs in a state that is optimal for flying mice and other related species.
The population of flying mice in Scotland and throughout the UK has declined significantly over the past century.
They are at risk of disappearance due to construction and development works that affect their habitat and the loss of the environment.
Wind turbines and lighting systems can be dangerous, as well as flies adhesive tape, chemical processing of building materials, and cat hunting.
In fact, flying mice are not blind.
However, their night hunting habits are such that their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to hunting for mining.
They use sophisticated echo-location techniques to accurately identify obstacles along the flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 significant gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes the population of flying mice very seriously.
