The organization even created Scotland’s first and only flying mice reservation at the Threave estate in Damfries and Galloway, where eight out of ten species of Scottish flying mice live.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is the ideal territory for them.
“Here, in Threave, is a great place for flying mice,” he says.
“There are old buildings, many old trees and all the elements of a good habitat.
But much about flying mice remains unknown, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need for a healthy existence.”
It reminds of the importance of checking the presence of flying mice before conducting technical maintenance within private holdings, as the unintentional destruction of one nest can lead to the death of up to 400 females and young individuals, and possibly even the destruction of the entire area.
Flying mice are protected by law, their destruction, grazing or destruction of their habitats is illegal.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish officer at the Flying Mouse Conservation Foundation, is calling on the public to help.
